Data Analysis and Visualization of the Financial Contribution of 2020’s Presidential Election Of the United States

May,13,2019

Abstract and Introduction

In this report we will try to explore and analyze the current situation of financial contribution for 2020’s presidential election.

In light of the summary above, Donald Trump get the most number of contributions and most contributors are from New York city, while California has the most contributors in all states. There are somethings wrong for the zip codes, 99999 and 4070 are evidently incorret. Most contribution amount are between 25 dollars and 80 dollars, and the average number is higher than this interval, 126.4 dollars. Interestingly, the most common occupation in the contributors is “RETIRED”.

This dataset has not provided the information about the candidiates’ gender and party, so we try to complement this part.

## check the values in cand_nm column for judging  their gender

## create a vector to store the female candidates' names
female_cand <- c("Gillibrand, Kirsten","Gabbard, Tulsi","Harris, Kamala D.",
                 "Klobuchar, Amy J.","Warren, Elizabeth ",
                 "Williamson, Marianne ")
## create a new column and fill this column with candidates' gender
## (based on their name)
df$cand_gender <- ifelse(df$cand_nm %in% female_cand,"Female","Male")
## i create a function here to tell which party they are belong to.
func <- function(i) 
{ifelse(i=="Trump, Donald J.","Republician",
          ifelse(i=="Sanders, Bernard","Independent","Democrats"))}
df$cand_party <- sapply(df$cand_nm,func)
## transform the data type to factor
df$cand_gender <- as.factor(df$cand_gender)
df$cand_party <- as.factor(df$cand_party)
## check the data again
str(df)

Analysis and Visualization

Univariate Analysis

The Distribution of Contribution Amount

ggplot(data=df,aes(x=contb_receipt_amt))+geom_histogram(color="white")+
  scale_x_log10(breaks= c(1,5,10,15,20,40,30,50,100,1000))+
  ggtitle("The Distribution of the Contribution Receipt Amount")
## Warning in self$trans$transform(x): 产生了NaNs
## Warning: Transformation introduced infinite values in continuous x-axis
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 45668 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

After adjusting the x-axis most of data fall in the interval between 1 and 1000. This distribution is a bit left skewed. We can see the most contibutions are between 20 and 40, the second most on count are between 40 dollars to about 100 dollars.

The distribution of the Contribution time

# transform the factor to datetime
Sys.setlocale("LC_TIME", "C")
## [1] "C"
df$contb_receipt_dt <- as.Date(df$contb_receipt_dt,"%d-%b-%y")
# plot
ggplot(data=df,aes(x=contb_receipt_dt))+geom_histogram(color="white")+
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 months")+
  ggtitle("The Distribution Of Contribution Receipt Time")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

From the figure above we can observe two peaks, one is at the end of 2016 and the beginning of 2017, after that the number of financial contributions fell back to a relatively low level but still increased slowly hereafter. The other peak is at the recent three months the number of contributions have risen to the highest position since the end of 2016.

In this dataset only Donald Trump belongs to Republician Party. It is consistent with the data of the count of the contributions to different political parties, the count of the contributions to Trump is much bigger than all other’s sum.

Double variables Analysis and Visualization

The Total, Average And Median of Contribution Receipt Amount In Every State.

## group and aggregate
df_by_states <- df %>%
  group_by(contbr_st) %>%
  summarise(total_amt=sum(contb_receipt_amt),
            mean_amt=mean(contb_receipt_amt),
            median_amt=median(contb_receipt_amt),
            n=n())
df_by_states <- subset(df_by_states,
                       contbr_st %in% abb & ! contbr_st %in% c("HI", "AK"))
map <- map_data("state")
data(state)
states <- data.frame(state.abb,state.name)
states$state.name <- tolower(states$state.name)
map <- merge(map,states,by.x="region",by.y="state.name",all.x=TRUE)
df_1 <- merge(map,df_by_states,by.x="state.abb",by.y="contbr_st",all.x=TRUE)
df_1 <- arrange(df_1,group,order)
ggplot(data=df_1,aes(x=long,y=lat,group=group))+
  geom_polygon(aes(fill=total_amt),color="gray")+
  coord_map("mercator")+
  scale_fill_gradient(low="#6495ED",high="#00008B")+
  ggtitle("Total Contribution Receipt Amount by States")

Based on the total number, California contributes the most of fund in all states, the other states with realatively darker color are Texas, New York Massachusetts and Florida.

ggplot(data=df_1,aes(x=long,y=lat,group=group))+
  geom_polygon(aes(fill=mean_amt),color="gray")+
  coord_map("mercator")+
  scale_fill_gradient(low="#90EE90",high="#006400")+
  ggtitle("Average Contribution Receipt Amount by States")

Averagely, the contribution amount in Massachusetts is the highest in all states, other states like California, Washington, Colorado, Minnesota, and New York also worth notice.

ggplot(data=df_1,aes(x=long,y=lat,group=group))+
  geom_polygon(aes(fill=median_amt),color="gray")+
  coord_map("mercator")+
  scale_fill_gradient(low="#FFFF00",high="#DAA520")+
  ggtitle("Median Contribution Receipt Amount by States")

The median contribution amount of every state as above.

Are There Any Difference On Contributors’ Occupations Between Different Political Parties?

# create a wordcloud with wordcloud library
library(wordcloud)
## Loading required package: RColorBrewer
occ_rep <- count(
  subset(df,cand_party=="Republician"& ! contbr_occupation=="" & 
           ! contbr_occupation=="INFORMATION REQUESTED"),contbr_occupation)
wordcloud(words = occ_rep$contbr_occupation, 
          freq = occ_rep$n, max.words =150,min.freq=3,colors = "blue")

occ_dem <- count(subset(df,
                        cand_party=="Democrats"& ! contbr_occupation=="" & 
                          ! contbr_occupation=="INFORMATION REQUESTED" ),
                 contbr_occupation)
wordcloud(words = occ_dem$contbr_occupation, 
          freq = occ_dem$n, 
          max.words =150,scale=c(2,.5),
          min.freq=3,colors = "RED")

The most common occupation is Retired, or Not employed, for both republician and democrats. if we just see those employed:
The common occupations of contributors to republician:
entrepreneur,homemaker, contractor, business owner, physician, teacher, attorney…
The common occupations of contributors to democrats:
attorney, consultant, professor, physician, software engineer,writer….
The gap is not so clear as expected before. I think other factor like the general political leanings in different states will have an influence.

How Does The Contribution Receipt Amount Change With Time?

ggplot(data=df,aes(x=contb_receipt_dt,y=contb_receipt_amt))+
  geom_line(stat = "summary",fun.y=sum)+
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 months")+
  ggtitle("Total Contribution Receipt Amount")

ggplot(data=df,aes(x=contb_receipt_dt,y=contb_receipt_amt))+
  geom_line(stat = "summary",fun.y=mean)+
  scale_x_date(date_breaks = "3 months")+
  ggtitle("Average Contributon Receipt Amount")

The second figure above is very simillar to the histogram of contribution time distribution, but from the third picture we find the average amount in recent three month is at a low level, this indicates that the big leap in the recent three months is mainly attributed to the increasing of the amount of contributors, not the average contribution amount.

Multivariables Analysis

What Is The Political Leaning In Different States?

## create 2 temp dataframe
df_rep_total <- subset(df,cand_party=="Republician") %>%
  group_by(contbr_st) %>%
  summarise(total_amt=sum(contb_receipt_amt))

df_dem_total <- subset(df,cand_party=="Democrats") %>%
  group_by(contbr_st) %>%
  summarise(total_amt=sum(contb_receipt_amt))
## merge 2 temp dataframe
df_bias <- merge(df_rep_total, df_dem_total, by.x="contbr_st", by.y="contbr_st")
rm(df_rep_total)
rm(df_dem_total)
## draw the plot
df_bias$prop_of_Dem_amt <- df_bias$total_amt.y/
  (df_bias$total_amt.x+df_bias$total_amt.y)
df_bias <- subset(df_bias, contbr_st %in% abb & ! contbr_st %in% c("HI","AK"))
df_bias1 <- merge(map, df_bias,by.x="state.abb",by.y="contbr_st",all.x=TRUE)
df_bias1 <- arrange(df_bias1,group,order)
ggplot(data=df_bias1,aes(x=long,y=lat,group=group,fill=prop_of_Dem_amt))+
  geom_polygon(color="gray")+coord_map("mercator")+
  scale_fill_gradient2(low="blue",mid="white",high="red",midpoint = 0.5)+
  ggtitle("The Propotion of Contribution to Democrats by States")

I try to explore the current political leanings in different states through this dataset, my method is to calculate the propotion of those contribution to Democrats in the total contributions. The result is displyed above, the blue color indicates that propotion of contribution amount to democats is less tha 50%, while the red color means more than 50%.

We have analyzed the increase in recent 3 months, and now from the figure displayed above, this looks like it is a Democrats’ theme, high total, but relatively low mean value.The contributions to democrats take a jumping growth recently, while those to republician and independents remian “ordinary”. I doubt whether this phenomenon is mainly from California, since they have very simillar features on the data: mainly for democrats, big total, but the average is not very high.

We notice some features about the contribution to different parties and candidates from above 3 figures.
The contributions for Trump is keeping steady generally from end of 2016, although sometimes he will get a bit amount of contribution.
The contributions for Democrats candidates are mostly occured at relatively recent time since their announcement for 2020 US presidential campaign, but the features for these contributions are distinctive: mainly occured recently, averagely high(compared to those for republician), and numbers is currently small.

Reflections

The Difficulties in this project:
For I was not famillar with R at first, i came across many techniques problem with R, that’s a really tough process for me. In this project, I spent most of time in looking and solving the techniques problem.
What I achieved:
Learning how to code in R, how to handle the difficulties,obtain the skill to draw more complicated graph, improve the thoughts for data analysis.
The limitations and prosepct of this analysis.
Although we have a very big dataset with more than 720,000 obeservations, the limitations still exist. Our dataset can reflect the present situation, but the future is uncertain, for example, we note republician dominate currently, but democrats may reverse it in the future. So the further observation is needed. Besides, the political contribution is one way to reflect one’s political stance, but to what extent it can refelct one’s political stance still wait for research, for instance, we can explore the correlation between votes and contribution for this issue.
